<h2>Established heuristic frameworks</h2>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Source</th><th>What it gives</th><th>What we borrow</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Nielsen's 10 usability heuristics</strong> (1994) + the <strong>0–4 severity</strong> scale</td>
      <td>Broad usability rules; only #8 (aesthetic-and-minimalist) and #4 (consistency) are <em>visual</em>. Severity = cosmetic → catastrophe, a function of frequency × impact × persistence.</td>
      <td>The <strong>severity scale</strong>, not the heuristic list (it's a usability, not a visual, rubric).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>CRAP</strong> (Contrast / Repetition / Alignment / Proximity) + extensions (hierarchy, balance, whitespace, type scale)</td>
      <td>The compact <em>visual</em> vocabulary most "does this look designed" critiques actually use.</td>
      <td>The backbone of the scored axes.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Gestalt</strong> (proximity, similarity, closure, common-region, figure-ground, focal point)</td>
      <td>Perceptual grounding for grouping/structure judgments.</td>
