<h2>The load-bearing finding — the split is three tiers, not two</h2>
<p>
  Mature evaluation tools partition design-quality signals into three tiers, and a rubric whose dimensions
  are <strong>tagged with their tier</strong> can route cheaply (DOM checks → pixel metrics → VLM):
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Tier A — deterministic from DOM/CSS</strong> (no vision): WCAG contrast ratios, spacing on a
    grid (8pt), type-scale ratios, touch-target sizes, design-token usage vs hard-coded values. The
    Lighthouse / <code>axe-core</code> surface — axe catches ~57% of WCAG issues at 100% precision and
    explicitly returns <em>"incomplete"</em> for what it can't be sure of.</li>
  <li><strong>Tier B — algorithmic-perceptual from pixels</strong> (vision <em>algorithms</em>, still
    deterministic, no LLM): the <strong>Aalto Interface Metrics</strong> (AIM, UIST'18) surface — visual
    clutter (feature congestion / subband entropy), colourfulness, symmetry, balance, grid-quality,
    figure-ground contrast, saliency, across four named categories (colour perception · perceptual fluency
    · visual guidance · accessibility).</li>
  <li><strong>Tier C — genuine perceptual judgment</strong> (needs a VLM or human): "hierarchy feels off",
    emphasis landing on the wrong element, overall polish/craft, crowding-in-context.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Output shape &amp; the VLM-trust finding</h2>
<p>
  <strong>UICrit</strong> (UIST'24) is the most directly relevant prior art: a human dataset of 3,059
  natural-language critiques over 983 Rico screens, scored on three 10-point dimensions
  (aesthetics / usability / overall), each critique carrying a <strong>bounding box + target scope</strong>
  (element / group / whole-screen / <em>missing</em>-element), post-hoc bucketed into ~5 categories
  (layout / colour-contrast / button-usability / learnability / text-readability). The proven output shape:
  <strong>a small closed set of scored dimensions + open-text localized findings tagged to a dimension,
  each with a severity.</strong> UICrit also found <strong>raw zero-shot VLM critique is poor</strong>
  (~13% of Gemini's comments valid), few-shot from a rubric lifts it ~55%, and <strong>humans still beat
  every automated method</strong> — so the rubric is what makes the Tier-C call trustworthy, and the
  human-correction loop (<a href="/backlog/1036-plateau-review-surface-view-a-page-critique-comment-correct-/">#1036</a>)
  is load-bearing, not a nicety.
</p>

<h2>Closed axes, open findings — diverging from the house default</h2>
<p>
  Scoring systems keep their axis set <strong>closed and small</strong> (AIM 4, Lighthouse 5, Nielsen 10)
  so scores stay comparable across pages and over time, and push all extensibility into the open-text
  findings underneath. This resolves the controlled-vocabulary / folksonomy split the <em>opposite</em> way
  from the corpus taxonomy's <a href="/research/design-ref-taxonomy/">grow-the-registry ruling</a> (#394) —
  deliberately, because the distillation corpus (#489/#490) needs comparable training pairs, which axis
  drift would destroy. A version bump is the escape hatch.
</p>

<h2>How "WE-grounded" works</h2>
<p>
  WE's differentiator is that its design standards are <strong>machine-readable</strong>, so the Tier-A
  checks aren't generic guesses — they're exact against what the page <em>declares</em>. The semantic-tier
  intents (<code>src/_data/intents.json</code>) map almost one-to-one onto critique dimensions:
  <code>typography</code> ("abstracting visual hierarchy from semantic HTML") grounds the type-scale and
  hierarchy axes; <code>density</code> ("spatial relationships, touch targets") grounds spacing;
  <code>layout</code> ("shell structure and regions") grounds alignment; <code>surface</code> ("Z-axis
  depth, material") grounds figure-ground; and the rendered-site a11y gate (#763/#770) already computes
  WCAG contrast deterministically, so the rubric <em>references</em> it rather than re-deriving it.
  Reading the standard as input is not <a href="/backlog/475-design-ref-vision-gated-capture-qc-candidate-surface-quality/">#475</a>-leakage —
  leakage is the standard <em>depending on</em> vision, which this never does.
</p>

<h2>What this feeds</h2>
<p>
  Three prepared forks in #1034: <strong>(F1)</strong> grounding model → <em>WE-grounded-layered</em>
  (generic-only discards WE's moat; conformance-only ignores that conformance ≠ good design — both flawed);
  <strong>(F2)</strong> own-vs-compose the deterministic checks → <em>compose</em> the existing a11y /
  token gates, own only the Tier-C judgment + synthesis (bias toward separation; don't re-implement
  #763/#770); <strong>(F3)</strong> output shape → <em>closed scored axes (1–5) + open localized findings
  (severity 0–4)</em>, versioned axis set. The proposed default vocabulary is 8 closed axes
  (contrast · spacing · alignment · type-scale · consistency · grouping · visual-hierarchy · polish), each
  tier-tagged and grounding-mapped. The rubric is <strong>not</strong> a <code>@webeverything</code>
  artifact — it's the output contract of the Plateau vision service (#475: vision is never a standard),
  riding the one <code>registerVisionProvider</code> seam (<code>scripts/design-refs/vision.mjs:143</code>).
</p>
